            "public_access_description": "The sites depicted on this tabletop are those visited  by Tsar Nicholas I on his Italian tour of 1845. In 1846 the Tsar commissioned a tabletop directly from Michelangelo Barberi; the artist called its composition 'Il bel cielo d'Italia' (the beautiful sky of Italy). The original table, with a central composition of a group of putti holding a portrait  of Tsarina Alexandra, is now at the Hermitage Museum in St. Petersburg. Its views match those of the present table, but are interspersed with symbolic images representing the Italian genius: works by famous Italian painters and portraits of illustrious figures.\n\nThe present work, made for Francis Needham, Earl Kilmorey, was exhibited in London at the Great Exhibition of 1851 where it received a Council Medal, the highest honour awarded.\n\nSir Arthur Gilbert and his wife Rosalinde formed one of the world's great decorative art collections, including silver, mosaics, enamelled portrait miniatures and gold boxes.  Arthur Gilbert donated his extraordinary collection to Britain in 1996.", 
            "exhibition_history": "Mosaici minuti romani del 700 et dell' 800 (Studio del Mosaico)\nThe Art of Mosaics and Monumental Silver (Los Angeles County Museum of Art 01/01/1986-31/12/1986)\nThe Art of Mosaics and Monumental Silver (Victoria and Albert Museum 01/01/1975-31/12/1979)\nThe Art of Mosaics and Monumental Silver (Victoria and Albert Museum 01/01/1975-31/12/1979)\nThe Art of Mosaics and Monumental Silver (Victoria and Albert Museum 01/01/1975-31/12/1979)\nThe Art of Mosaics and Monumental Silver (Victoria and Albert Museum 01/01/1975-31/12/1979)\nMosaics from the Gilbert Collection (Victoria and Albert Museum 16/07/1975-31/12/1979)\nThe Gilbert Mosaic Collection (Los Angeles County Museum of Art 14/01/1975-02/03/1975)", 
